<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-900-390  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 900 390.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 20 1989 v6 n46 p29(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New line of Psion portables boasts EPROM storage. (MC-200, MC-400and MC-600 with erasable, programmable, read-only memory) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sexton, Tara.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Psion Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Psion MC 200 (Portable computer) (product introduction)Psion MC 400 (Portable computer) (product introduction)Psion MC 600 (Portable computer) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Portable computersProduct IntroductionEPROM.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Tara SextonandM;Hoping to carve a niche for itself in the portable PC arena, Psion Inc. lastweek introduced a new line of portable computers that use an alternative toconventional hard and floppy disks.andM;The new notebook-sized machines combine flash memory with an erasable,programmable, read-only memory (EPROM) data-storage system developed inconjunction with Intel Corp. and Microsoft Corp.andM;The matchbook-sized solid-state disks replace conventional, mechanical diskdrives and provide faster read/write times than other EPROM devices, companyofficials said.andP;  The solid-state disks can hold up to 512K bytes of data.andM;The new 4.5-pound machines -- the MC-200, the MC-400 and the MC-600 -- can bepowered for up to 60 hours by eight AA batteries, officials said.andM;&quot;Standard disk drives on portable computers have problems,&quot; said BillySkyrme, president of the Watertown, Conn., firm.andP;  He explained thatmechanical devices are more susceptible to crashes.andM;PC vendors agreed that hard disks can be easily damaged, but challenged theclaim that EPROM is a good alternative.andM;&quot;Disk drives are more flexible than EPROM technology,&quot; said John Blakely, aproduct manager for Chips andamp; Technologies Inc., the San Jose, Calif., chipmaker.andP;  Disk drives also feature larger capacities than the EPROM devices, hesaid.andM;The $799 MC-200 comes with 128K bytes of RAM and an LCD screen with CGAgraphics.andP;  The $1,499 MC-400 features 256K bytes of RAM.andP;  The $2,499 MC-600comes with 768K bytes of RAM and an LCD screen with CGA graphics.andP;  All of themachines are powered by a 7.68MHz processor and feature two expansion slots.andM;To adapt its new technology for use in other computers, Psion has alsodesigned a $150 external solid-state disk that operates as a stand-alone3-1/2-inch drive.andM;Psion can be reached at (203) 274-7521.andO;</TEXT></DOC>